&lt;h2 id="411">4.1.1&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>For the next chapter we need to prepare our applications to run in a cloud environment. One important aspect of this will be adding health checks to our applications. Implementing or adding health checks to your Quarkus application is - as expected - easy. Simply add the extension &amp;lsquo;smallrye-health&amp;rsquo; to your applications with the following command:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">
./mvnw quarkus:add-extension -Dextensions&lt;span style="color:#ce5c00;font-weight:bold">=&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#4e9a06">&amp;#34;quarkus-smallrye-health&amp;#34;&lt;/span>
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>When you restart your applications they both will expose automatically the &amp;lsquo;/health&amp;rsquo; endpoint which indicates that the application is up and running.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Additionally we need to configure the connection from our data-consumer to the data-producer. As for now the data-consumer simply points to the url configured in the &lt;code>application.properties&lt;/code> which gets injected to the defined RestClient.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Extend your application.properties of the data-consumer to:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code class="language-java" data-lang="java">
